Rating: 0
I read all of the reviews and decided to see what the great Julia Child says about macaroons. I followed her lead and I had none of the problems mentioned by the others. As she instructs, I rubbed the bowl with 1 Tb of vinegar and 1 tsp of salt. I then omitted the salt in the whites. I added just shy of a 1/4 tsp creme of tartar when the whites were just beginning to foam. I also added all of the confectioners sugar to the pulsing of the almonds. I forgot to buy food coloring so I didn't have that added liquid as one reader mentioned. My whites never deflated. They are beautiful and delicious. Gluten Free as well! Makes 50 (quarter size) cookies.

Rating: 4
Made these last night and they turned out pretty good. I only did one batch, but it was a good learning experience. First, I wisked the almond puree and sifted the powdered sugar into the almond puree as I was wisking. This cut down on the lumps. Second, I added liquid food coloring, which made them a little wet. Next time, I'm going to use gel food color to see if that helps. Third, I was having trouble with the bottoms sticking to the parchment paper, so I let the last batch cool on the cookie sheet instead of a rack, and they released perfectly! Last, Do not let the mixture sit. Pipe it all at once even if you have to let some trays rest longer than others. If not, I noticed that the dough cracked some when it was first put in the oven. Also, I made double the ganache and added more of the raspberry extract until I could distinctly taste it. It tastes AMAZING with the sweet and saltiness of the macarons! In love!

